		<item>
			<title>Govt determined to stop terrorism - Ashiru</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175350-govt-determined-to-stop-terrorism-ashiru</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175350-govt-determined-to-stop-terrorism-ashiru</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<p>Honoring the victims of the August 26, 2011, United Nations Building bombing in Abuja on Monday, the Minister of Foreign Affairs Olugbenga Ashiru reiterated the determination of government to fight the scourge of terrorism.<br /><br />“The government of Nigeria is determined to really handle this scourge head on, and I believe we are making steady progress in securing lives and properties not just within Abuja but in the affected areas of the country”.</p>
<p>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AQMcEuAInEU<br /><br />During a memorial ceremony held at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs as part of events organized by the UN to commemorate the casualties and injured persons after the ill-fated suicide attack, the Foreign Affairs Minister also expressed government’s commitment to continue working with the United Nations and its agencies.<br /><br />“Terrorism is a crime against humanity, and we all stand as one in Nigeria with members of the international community, the UN and other countries, to condemn and continue to support the UN and all its programs and activities.”He said.<br /><br />Also speaking at the event, the Minister for the Federal Capital Territory, Bala Mohammed, while commemorating the victims, said government has already earmarked 2.6 billion naira for the rehabilitation and enhancement of the building.<br /><br />He said government is committed to working with the UN organization and is determined to carry the responsibility of renovating the building and paying for the treatment of injured victims. <br /><br />He stressed that, “for the building we have already provided 2.6 billion naira for the rehabilitation of the building in addition to the 500 or 600 million naira that the president had earlier approved for the renting of alternative places carrying it to about 3.2 billion naira, so before the end of the year, Julius Berger is already mobilizing.”</p>
<p>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SFAhgg9r0K8<br /><br />Speaking earlier, the UN resident coordinator Mr. Daouda Toure, thanked the Nigerian government for its support and reiterated the determination of the organization to carry on its programs for the benefit of humanity.<br /> <br />He remarked that, “our spirit has not been dampened” adding that “our departed colleagues sacrifice will not be in vain”.<br /> <br />An Injured victim of the bombing, and a staff of the United Nations Mr. Agbo John Paul, who gave the vote of thanks at the event, while looking back at the suicide attack exactly one year ago, narrated his ordeal to Daily trust online. He said the event has shattered and altered his life and that of many of the victims.</p>
<p>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zv3TcZwg24E</p>]]></description>
			<author>ronaldmutum@yahoo.co.uk (Ronald Mutum)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Mon, 27 Aug 2012 14:38:21 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>Kaduna to generate 30 megawatts solar energy</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175299-kaduna-to-generate-30-megawatts-solar-energy</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175299-kaduna-to-generate-30-megawatts-solar-energy</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">The Kaduna State government will soon generate 30 megawatts of electricity through solar energy, Governor Patrick Yakowa said in Kaduna yesterday.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;" />

A statement by Yakowa’s Senior Special Assistant on Media Reuben Buhari said the governor signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MoU) with a German company (Helios Energy) on the solar energy generation in Abuja on Friday.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The statement said the MoU was signed under the Nigerian-German Energy Partnership, where the German company was expected to spend about 50 million Euros to construct the facility.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The project would be executed under a Build, Operate and Transfer (BOT) scheme that would last for 25 years.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It said Kaduna government would provide about 60 hectares of land needed for the facility, while the German company would train Kaduna State indigenes in Germany on how to operate the facility upon its completion.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The statement quoted Yakowa as saying that additional 30 megawatts into the state’s power supply would boost economic activities.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">According to him, the solar energy project will strengthen his administration’s tripartite focus on security, unity and development.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">It further said that Yakowa expressed delight with the agreement, adding that his administration “will continue to explore more ways of complementing the current source of power supply so that the industrial sector of the state will flourish’’.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">On his part, Dr. Jeremy Gaines, the Coordinator of the Nigerian-German Energy Partnership said in the statement that the partnership would boost economic activities of Kaduna State and further attract foreign direct investment.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The statement said the company would identify suitable site for the facility in October for the immediate take-off of the project.(NAN)</p>
<pre><br /></pre>]]></description>
			<author>tunde@dailytrust.com (Nan)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Sun, 26 Aug 2012 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>Jigawa spends N2.5bn on scholarship</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175301-jigawa-spends-n25bn-on-scholarship</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175301-jigawa-spends-n25bn-on-scholarship</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">The Jigawa State government says it spent N2. 5 billion on different scholarship programmes for its students from 2007 to date.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"> </p>

State Commissioner of Education Prof. Haruna Wakili said in Dutse yesterday at the inauguration of the new site of Dutse Model International School that between 2011 and 2012 no fewer than 307 students from the state were sponsored abroad to study Medicine, Engineering, ICT and Islamic studies.
<p> </p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">He said the government’s spending on students studying in the country had increased from N43 .5 million in 2007 to N734 .5 million in 2011, saying tertiary institutions also received a boost as government recently earmarked N1.1 billion for the establishment of College of Remedial Studies in Kafin-Hausa.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">He said the institution would take off in September and the government budget on education had increased from seven per cent in 2007 to 29.1 per cent in 2012. (NAN)</p>]]></description>
			<author>tunde@dailytrust.com (Nan)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Sun, 26 Aug 2012 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>NDLEA to end abuse of unconventional substances –Giade</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175302-ndlea-to-end-abuse-of-unconventional-substances-giade</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175302-ndlea-to-end-abuse-of-unconventional-substances-giade</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;">NDLEA Chairman Ahmadu Giade has vowed to put an end to the abuse of narcotic drugs and unconventional substances in some parts of the country.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;" />

This was contained in a statement by the agency’s spokesman, Mr Mitchell Ofoyeju, in Lagos yesterday. Giade said substances like rubber solution, petrol, lizard dung and pit toilet were regularly abused in some parts of Nigeria, particularly in Kano State.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">“We are determined to stop the abuse of narcotics and unconventional substances such as rubber solution, petrol, lizard dung and pit toilet, all in a bid to get high. All hands must be on deck to protect lives from destruction.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">“It is unhygienic, harmful and unacceptable. We will not fold our hands and watch our youths get involved in such unworthy practices,” Giade said.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The chairman identified men, particularly transporters, as those sniffing petrol, toilet and lizard dung to get high before embarking on driving.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Giade noted that the possibility of culprits contacting various sicknesses and diseases from the act.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">He urges parents to watch their children with a view to checking their involvement in the unhealthy practice. (NAN)</p>]]></description>
			<author>tunde@dailytrust.com (Nan)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Sun, 26 Aug 2012 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>Convoy accidents: FRSC ‘shame register’ dormant</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175304-convoy-accidents-frsc-shame-register-dormant</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175304-convoy-accidents-frsc-shame-register-dormant</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[The ‘shame register’ introduced by the Federal Road Safety Corps (FRSC) in December 2011 is seemingly ineffective following increase in convoy accidents resulting from dangerous driving.
<p style="text-align: justify;" />

The register was introduced by the Corps to shame highly placed individuals whose convoys drive recklessly.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The Corps Marshal of the FRSC Osita Chidoka said the details of vehicles of top government personnel found guilty of violating traffic regulations written in the Corps ‘shame register’ will be made public.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">“But eight months after the declaration, the Corps hasn’t shamed any convoy driver in spite of their flagrant abuse of traffic regulations,” one FRSC personnel said.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Another source said, “convoy drivers were not ‘shamed’ because none was found guilty of any offence” and that the ‘shame’ register “was mostly functional during festivities.”</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Convoy drivers particularly the governors’ drivers have blamed their superiors of forcing them to over speed and disregard traffic regulations, FRSC report on convoy drivers training recently said. The Corps had conducted refresher training for convoy drivers last year during which a number of governors’ driver who attended said their principals mostly instruct them to drive faster. The report said the drivers whose health conditions are mostly unsound following poor remuneration and inadequate medical tests confessed that their superiors would often instruct them to move at high speed to catch appointments.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">When Daily Trust contacted the FRSCs Road Transport Safety Standardization Scheme office in Abuja which also organizes convoy drivers’ training for details about its previous reports, the officials said the report hasn’t been made available to the public and apart from convoy drivers; they also conducted trainings for tanker and commercial bus drivers.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Head of the Scheme, Kayode Olagunju, said he was not authorized to make the outcome of the trainings public. However Premium Times news agency quoted the report was sent to the Rivers State Governor Rotimi Amechi. “Some of the drivers claimed they were usually forced to drive above the stipulated speed limits to catch up appointments and that safety was not always the major concern of their principals,” the FRSC said in its report, a copy which was sent to the governor who heads the Governors’ Forum.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Between 2008 to date, 12 state governors’ convoys were involved in accidents including one involving Katsina State government vehicles, many of them fatal, with 2012 alone recording three, as of June. A road crash involving five vehicles belonging to Jigawa State government occurred last week near Kano.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The crashes have killed 17 people and left many injured. And in nearly all of the cases, witnesses blamed the convoys.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">FRSC said it found that dozens of the drivers, many who are poorly remunerated, to have abnormal eyesight and dangerously high blood pressure, with nearly 300 drivers having got their jobs either without a driver’s licenses or with expired permits. One driver from Yobe State, apparently the worst case, had his last license renewal in1998.</p>]]></description>
			<author>tunde@dailytrust.com (Misbahu Bashir)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Sun, 26 Aug 2012 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>N5000 note rubbishes ‘cashless’ policy - ACN</title>
			<link>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175305-n5000-note-rubbishes-cashless-policy-acn</link>
			<guid>http://www.dailytrust.com.ng/index.php/news/175305-n5000-note-rubbishes-cashless-policy-acn</guid>
			<description><![CDATA[The Action Congress of Nigeria (ACN) has asked the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) to rethink its plan to introduce N5000 denomination into the nation’s currency system as it could harm the economy.
<p style="text-align: justify;" />

The party said the unintended consequences and collateral damage of introducing the N5000 note and other restructuring of the nation’s currencies in 2013 may far outweigh the benefits of the new measure.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">In a statement yesterday, ACN national publicity secretary, Alhaji Lai Mohammed said while the introduction of new note may serve the dual purpose of raising revenue for government on one hand and reducing the cost of transactions on the other hand, it among others often signifies a regime of increased and sustained fiscal deficit financing of an economy.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">“Secondly the issuance of such high value currency notes is likely to be perceived as an indication of government’s failure to effectively control inflation. Unfortunately once this perception takes hold, increased inflation expectations can be built up quite rapidly and these have pushed many countries into a situation of hyper-inflation in the past, which has typically culminated in the redenomination or even complete abandonment of the entire currency system.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">“Thirdly the issuance of the N5, 000 currency notes runs counter to the recent policy of the CBN to promote a “cashless” economy by encouraging the increased use of non-cash transaction instruments. This policy which is aimed at reducing the use of cash had been justified by the need to reduce the burden of the cost of printing and distributing currency notes. The introduction of a high face value currency note actually does the opposite because by reducing the unit cost of printing and transportation, it actually would promote the use of cash,” Mohammed said.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">While saying that there is a close relationship between inflation and issuance of high value currency notes, he listed some countries across the world to buttress his claim.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">He said, “Between 1975 and 1991, Argentina experienced a period of inflation during which increasingly higher face value notes were issued. At the beginning of 1975, the highest denomination in Argentina was 1,000 pesos. This rose to 5,000 pesos in late 1976, then to 10,000 pesos in 1979 and rose further to 1,000,000 in 1981. As this trend became clearly unsustainable, a series of currency reforms followed. This did not curb the inflation.”</p>]]></description>
			<author>tunde@dailytrust.com (Abbas Jimoh)</author>
			<category>News</category>
			<pubDate>Sun, 26 Aug 2012 23:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		</item>
